# Room 18 Wireshark: The Basics

## Task 1 Introduction

- Wireshark is an open-source, cross-platform packet analyzer.
- It captures live traffic and inspects PCAP files.
- Learning Objectives: navigate and configure Wireshark, inspect packets across TCP/IP layers, apply display filters.
- Prerequisites: basic networking knowledge.
- Environment: VM with http1.pcapng and Exercise.pcapng.

---

## Task 2 Tool Overview

- Use Cases: troubleshoot network issues, detect anomalies, study protocols.
- Note: Wireshark is not an IDS; it only analyzes packets.
- GUI Sections: toolbar, display filter bar, recent files, capture interfaces, status bar.
Features:
- Load PCAP files.
- Three panes: packet list, packet details, packet bytes.
- Packet coloring (temporary and permanent rules).
- Live sniffing (start/stop/restart).
- Merge PCAP files.
- View file properties (hash, capture time, stats).

---

## Task 3 Packet Dissection

- Packet dissection = protocol breakdown using OSI layers.
- Example HTTP packet shows 7 layers:
- Frame (Layer 1) → physical info.
- Source MAC (Layer 2) → MAC addresses.
- Source IP (Layer 3) → IPv4 addresses.
- Protocol (Layer 4) → TCP/UDP ports.
- Protocol Errors → TCP reassembly.
- Application Protocol (Layer 5) → HTTP, FTP, SMB.
- Application Data → application-specific content.
- Clicking details highlights corresponding bytes.

---

## Task 4 Packet Navigation

- Packet Numbers: each packet gets a unique ID.
- Go to Packet: jump directly to a packet or conversation.
- Find Packets: search by content (filters, hex, string, regex).
- Mark Packets: highlight packets of interest (lost after closing file).
- Packet Comments: persistent notes inside capture files.
- Export Packets: save only relevant packets.
- Export Objects: extract transferred files (HTTP, SMB, TFTP).
- Time Display Format: change from “seconds since capture” to UTC.
- Expert Info: highlights anomalies with severity (Chat, Note, Warn, Error).

---

## Task 5 Packet Filtering

Two filter types:
- Capture filters: applied during capture.
- Display filters: applied during viewing.
- Apply as Filter: right-click a field to filter.
- -Conversation Filter: show all packets in a conversation.
- Colourise Conversation: highlight related packets without filtering.
- Prepare as Filter: create but don’t apply immediately.
- Apply as Column: add fields as columns in packet list.
- Follow Stream: reconstruct application-level traffic (TCP/UDP/HTTP).
Simple Queries:
- By protocol: http, arp, dhcp, ftp, smtp, pop, imap.
- By port: tcp.port == 80.
- By IP: ip.addr == 192.168.1.2.

